<script>q("talkPage.init", {
	"el": "[data-talk-page]",
	"__INITIAL_DATA__": {"comments":{"id":27733,"count":4,"talk_id":9473},"threadId":27733,"current_talk":"9473","description":"Danielle Wood leads the Space Enabled research group at the MIT Media Lab, where she works to tear down the barriers that limit the benefits of space exploration to only the few, the rich or the elite. She identifies six technologies developed for space exploration that can contribute to sustainable development across the world -- from observation satellites that provide information to aid organizations to medical research on microgravity that can be used to improve health care on Earth. \"Space truly is useful for sustainable development for the benefit of all peoples,\" Wood says.","event":"TEDNYC","language":"en","name":"Danielle Wood: 6 space technologies we can use to improve life on Earth","slug":"danielle_wood_how_we_can_use_space_technology_to_improve_life_on_earth","speakers":[{"id":"3758","slug":"danielle_wood","is_published":true,"firstname":"Danielle","lastname":"Wood","middleinitial":"","title":"","description":"Space engineer and development scholar","photo_url":"https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/deca48e2bc0245a0b651395519b6c3c874b71ba1_254x191.jpg","whatotherssay":"","whotheyare":"Danielle Wood designs satellites and space technology applications that contribute to sustainable development. ","whylisten":"<p>Dr. Danielle Wood has published extensive, novel research findings on emerging space activity in Africa, Latin America and South East Asia; advised senior leaders in the US government on technology policy and led teams of engineers and scientists to create satellite systems that contribute to public safety. As of January 2018, Dr. Wood directs the Space Enabled Research Group and serves as an Assistant Professor at the Media Lab in the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in Cambridge, Massachusetts, USA. The Mission of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.media.mit.edu/groups/space-enabled/overview/\" target=\"_blank\">Space Enabled research group</a>&nbsp;is to advance justice in earth&#39;s complex systems using designs enabled by space. At Space Enabled, Wood designs innovative systems that harness space technology that support work toward the United Nations&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/sustainable-development-goals/\" target=\"_blank\">Sustainable Development Goals</a>.</p><p>Wood&#39;s research also develops systems analysis tools to improve decision making during the design of complex systems. Most recently, she worked as the Applied Sciences Manager within the Earth Science Division of Goddard Space Flight Center. Previously, she served as Special Assistant and Advisor to the Deputy Administrator at NASA Headquarters in Washington, DC. Prior to working at NASA, Wood held positions at the Aerospace Corporation, Johns Hopkins University and the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.unoosa.org/\" target=\"_blank\">United Nations Office of Outer Space Affairs</a>. She studied at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where she earned a PhD in engineering systems, SM in aeronautics and astronautics, SM in technology policy and SB in aerospace engineering.</p>"}],"url":"https://www.ted.com/talks/danielle_wood_how_we_can_use_space_technology_to_improve_life_on_earth","viewed_count":1052896,"talks":[{"recommendations":{"status":"approved","headline":"Danielle Wood recommends","blurb":"More resources curated by Danielle Wood","start_at":null,"end_at":null,"published":true,"eyebrow":"","type":"recommendation","rec_lists":[{"title":"","description":"","rec_items":[{"label":"EXPLORE","headline":"The Space Enabled Research Group at the MIT Media Lab in Cambridge, Massachusetts","blurb":"Learn more about the work of Professor Wood in the Space Enabled Research Group at the MIT Media Lab. The mission of Space Enabled is to advance justice in earth’s complex systems using designs enabled by space. Dr. Wood and her team accomplish this mission by combining skills in satellite engineering, complex systems modeling, social science and user-centered design.","note":"","link_url":"https://www.media.mit.edu/groups/space-enabled/overview/","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""},{"label":"READ_Article","headline":"\"Building technological capability within satellite programs in developing countries\"","blurb":"Dr. Wood explains the ways that space technology contributes to development and improves life on earth. Chapters 1 and 2 provide an overview of key changes in the space sector as smaller, cheaper satellites become more accessible to countries around the world. Dr. Wood also gives detailed case studies showing how new countries are increasing their participation in satellite engineering and applying space technology for development.","note":"Danielle Wood\r\nMassachusetts Institute of Technology, 2012","link_url":"http://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/79502","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""},{"label":"EXPLORE","headline":"The International Telecommunication Union Deploys Satellite Communication to Support Disaster Recovery","blurb":"Natural disasters such as hurricanes, earthquakes and floods often damage communications infrastructure. The International Telecommunications Union is one of the organizations that deploys satellite communication systems and other information technologies in countries that are impacted by natural disasters. Read examples of ITU activities to provide satellite-based telephones in nations around the world during disaster recovery.","note":"","link_url":"https://www.itu.int/en/ITU-D/Emergency-Telecommunications/Pages/Response.aspx","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""},{"label":"EXPLORE","headline":"Satellite Earth Observation Supports Societal Benefits, NASA Applied Sciences","blurb":"The NASA Applied Sciences Program, within the NASA Earth Science Division, works to promote the use of satellite-based earth observation and models for societal benefit. The program funds research, outreach and training in the areas of ecological forecasting, water resources, [disasters](https://disasters.nasa.gov/), agriculture and health and air quality.","note":"","link_url":"https://appliedsciences.nasa.gov/","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""},{"label":"EXPLORE","headline":"Microgravity Research on the International Space Station brings Benefits in Health, Materials Science and Manufacturing","blurb":"The Center for Advancement of Science in Space (CASIS) is a non-profit organization that manages access to the research facilities on the US Laboratory within the International Space Station. CASIS helps companies and researchers prepare and operate research experiments on the International Space Station in the microgravity environment, where the impacts of earth’s gravity are not felt. Scientists have completed projects that support drug development, advanced materials, medicine and earth observation.","note":"","link_url":"https://www.iss-casis.org/","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""},{"label":"EXPLORE","headline":"NASA Spinoff","blurb":"In the annual Spinoff publication, NASA showcases exciting examples of NASA technology, engineering methods and science findings that have been transferred from the space sector to be used for societal benefit. Read about advances in health, public safety and consumer goods that were enabled by NASA technology. You can also search the NASA Spinoff database to find more stories in your field of interest. Search the NASA software and patent catalogs to find tools you can use in your.","note":"","link_url":"https://spinoff.nasa.gov/","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""},{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"*Stamped from the Beginning: The Definitive History of Racist Ideas in America*","blurb":"Space technology is not yet benefiting communities around the globe to an equal extent. Historical forces driven by racist and colonialist ideas have created systems of education, commerce and international cooperation that concentrated control of advanced technology into hands of the wealthy and elite. Ibram Kendi’s deeply researched book, Stamped from the Beginning, provides insightful historical analysis that helps explain how racist ideas have been employed by those with economic and political power in order to maintain their position. Although this book is not explicitly about access to technology, it is a must read for those who wish to understand how racial inequality has been consistently maintained by discrimination and racist ideas. The book argues that we can pursue equality by acknowledging our deeply held racist ideas and consciously practicing antiracist thinking to design antiracist policies.","note":"Ibram X. Kendi\r\nNation Books, 2017","link_url":"https://www.amazon.com/Stamped-Beginning-Definitive-History-National/dp/1568585985/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""}]}]},"more_resources":[],"corrections":[],"has_citations":true,"take_action":[{"status":"approved","blurb":"**Join** citizen scientists around the world by contributing to challenges and contests from NASA. Use NASA data and technology to help society and advance space research.","link_url":"https://www.nasa.gov/solve/index.html","visible_url":"nasa.gov","start_at":null,"end_at":null,"published":true,"eyebrow":"","type":"take_action","verb":"join"},{"status":"approved","blurb":"**Follow** Danielle Wood on Twitter.","link_url":"https://twitter.com/space_enabled","visible_url":"@space_enabled","start_at":null,"end_at":null,"published":true,"eyebrow":null,"type":"take_action","verb":"follow"},{"status":"approved","blurb":"**Follow** Danielle Wood on Instagram.","link_url":"https://www.instagram.com/space.enabled/","visible_url":"instagram.com/space.enabled","start_at":null,"end_at":null,"published":true,"eyebrow":null,"type":"take_action","verb":"follow"}],"curator_approved":true,"description":"Danielle Wood le